EPA is proposing to treat Tribes in the same manner as States for the purposes of both section 116 of the Act and for all
of the CAA preemption provisions, including provisions such as section 177 that authorize exclusions from preemption
provisions. This will clarify EPA's position that Tribes like States generally have authority to exceed minimum
Federal requirements. It will also clarify the fact that Tribes, like States, are preempted from imposing stricter
standards where Congress has so specified. This will advance the overarching purpose of the preemption provisions
to avoid undue barriers on the trade of goods in commerce. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
4. Provisions for Which no Separate Tribal Program Required.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Under some provisions of the CAA, Tribes would have a specific role by virtue of having met the minimum eligibility
requirements discussed in Part III.A, irrespective of whether a specific program is approved. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
For example, under section 107(d)(3), the Administrator would notify an eligible Tribe of information indicating
that an area within the Tribe's jurisdiction should be redesignated, and the Tribe would have an opportunity to provide
input on that redesignation in the same fashion as a State. Under section 107(d)(3) a Tribe could also submit a revised
designation of any area within its jurisdiction on its own motion. Similarly, under section 112(r)(7)(B)(iii),
risk management plans would be submitted to Tribal Emergency Response Commissions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Under sections 169B, 176A and 184 Tribes meeting eligibility requirements for such provisions shall be treated in
the same manner as States in identifying what areas should be included in interstate air pollution and visibility
transport regions and in establishing commission membership.
